summary:
I trained as a general and paediatric nurse before graduating both in medicine and cultural anthropology (specialisation medical anthropology). From 1994-2016, I worked as an assistant professor in Erasmus University Rotterdam, Institute of Health Policy and Management. In 2003, I was appointed professor 'Transitions in Care' at Rotterdam University of Applied Sciences, Research Center Innovations in Care. My research focus is on patients’ lived experiences with chronic illness, patient participation in care, and self-management support (including shared decision making). I have extensive experience in mixed methods research, including participatory approaches with patients, professionals and students, and in project management of large research consortia. I (co-)authored over 70 peer-reviewed research papers. In 2019, I received the first Dutch Delta Award, a national prize of €500K for excellence in combining applied research, practice improvement, and professional education.
Current research programs: 
(1) ‘On Your Own Feet’ (preferences and competencies of adolescents with chronic conditions in their transition to adulthood and adult care); 
(2) Self-management support of people with chronic conditions;
(3) 'Vitale Delta' (vitality and health).

